 bollovo the relations shoutd\nbo mutual. I don't think the corpora\ntlons nro entitled to moro than fair\ntreatment and If thoy get that they\nough to. ba-s.itistiou, A\" \"n-\nnlneloi, lnionigoni uuiruiv\"\n....ht tn note fnr Is lust treat\nment, and that he and his coropnny\nIs entitled to; nnu I oonovo ma\nmont of tho American pcoplo Is to\nconcede this.\n\"I nm an optimist In regard to tho\nultimate business outlook and bellove\nthat all questions will sooner or later\nbe adjusted on a basis which will hi\nmutually satisfactory to all.\"\nHoro to preside over tho conven\ntion of tho Association of Life Insur\nance Presidents, Morton refused to\ndiscuss tho possible effect further re\nvision of tho tariff would havo on\nbusiness, but assorted that now thn'\ntho Democrats worn In power, thc\nwould probably \"play politics.\"\nBECOME ANGRY\nAnd go Out Rioting And\nThrowing Bombs, Scores\nBeing Hurt And Proper\nty is Destroyed.\nt\nBy United Press Wire. v\nBoltast, Dec. 10. Political excite\nment Is at fever heat today, following\nlast night's riots that resulted when\nHovcral Orangemen voted for tho\nIrlsh-Natlonallst candidates. Those\nso voting aro. being called traitors\nMind their house's aro under gunrd to\nf prevent violence.\nScores wore hurt In last nights\nriots, rtevolvers. clubs and knives\nwero UBed frcoly and one bomb was\nthrown, Tho damage to property\nwill run far into tho thousands.\nThe Ornngomon aro against homo\nrulo and -their wrath whon It became\nknown that several of their number\nhad voted for tho Nationalists, whose\nslogan Is homo rulo, know no bounds.\nFrom the Scene of Explos\nion 6n Crow's Nest Pass.\nTen Dead.\nBy United Press Who.\nCalgary, Alberta, Dec. 10 Thirty of\n-\"tho forty-flvo nilners ontombed by a\ntorrlllo explosion In tho Western\nCanada collieries mine, on tho Crow's\nNost pass, had been romoyed by day\nbreak. Ton of them wero dond and\nof tho remainder ninny wero terribly\nburned, somo fatally.\nIRISHMEN\nTHIRTY\nMNERS\nREMOVED\nIt la not known what has happoneu\nto. the men left In tho mine, though\nJih'e rescuers have little hopo that\nftliey will bo able to reach thorn nllvo.\n'i'he explosion occurred at 7 o'clock\nlast night nnd wns followed by a\nlira which was extinguished only nf-\nter a hard tlghL It was several\nhours before\" tho first securing .party\nwas able to enter tho shaft.\nAll of the entrapped men wero for\neigners, mostly Italians nnd Swedes.\nNo one has been nbl0 to tell what\ncaused tho explosion.\nQUESTION OF STRIKE\nUP TO ENGINEERS\nBy United Press Wire.\nChicago, Dec. 10 Whether 33,700 lo\ncomotlvo engineers employed on sixty\nono western railroads nro In favor of\na strike to enforco demands for high\ner pay will bo decided hero today\nwhen President Warren A. Stone, of\ntho Brotherhood of Locomotlvo En\ngineers, nnd a number of system\nchairmen complete the count of a\nstrike vote tnken among tho men dur\ning tho pnst few weeks.\nIt Is predicted thnt the result of\ntho balloting will show moro than\nninety per cent, of tho engineers In\nfavor of tho strlko to enforco their\ndemand for a fifteen per cent rnlso In\npay nnd tho adjustment of work\ning conditions.\nShould tho strlko threat reach a\ncrisis, It Is believed llkelythat tho\nrnllroads will appeal to Chairman\nMartin A. Knnpp, of the Intcrstato\nCommerco commission, and Labor\nCommissioner Nelll for mcdlntlon nnd\narbitration under tho Erdmnn law.\nOLD FIGHT\nT THE\nMiddle Man Brought up\nAgain by Sir Horace\nPlunkett.\nBy United Tress Wire.\nNow York, Dec. 10 \"Unless tho\nAmerican farmer will organize and\ndlstrlhuto his own products thcro can\nbo no reduction In tho high cost of\nliving either hero or abroad\" said Sir\nHorace Plunkett, today. lie Is the\npresident of tho Irish Agricultural So\ncloty and originator of tho coopera\ntive dairies movement In Ireland. He\nIs In this country to urge the far\nmers to organize and do away with\ntho mlddlo man entirely.\n\"The fnrmers aro beginning to\nreallzo that their Inaction has been\nmore tho reason for the high cost of\nliving than tho trusts. Wo aro orga\nnizing on tho other side and If Amer\nican farmers will do tho same horo\nwith concerted action we can reduco\ntho cost of living very materially and\nalso permit tho farmer to make moro\nmoney than ho now docs, Inasmuch\nas Iho mlddlo man's profit will be\nsaved.\"\nSir Horace left hero this nfternoon\nfor Chlcngo by way of Washington.\nHo jilnns to spend two months in this\ncountry studying agricultural condi\ntions.\nDynamited Safe.\nRichmond, Ind Dec. 10 Yeggmen\ndynamited tho safo In tho Farmers'\nbank at Milton, near here, early this\nmorning and secured $500 In ensh.\nThoy escaped with u horso and buggj\nstolen from a levcry etuble.\nTho safo was demolished and the\nbank building partially wrecked. Tho\nexplosion wns heard by a number or\npersons, but no effort wns mado to\nstop tho robbers.\nIt Is behoved by tho authorities to\nbo tho work of tho gang -which ha\nbeen operating extensively In Ohio\nand wns last heard of when tho safe\nIn tho AVest Carrolltown, Ohio post\nolllco wob blown.\nNATIVES OF WEST AFRICA\nSLAYING FRENCH SOLDIERS\nPurls Dec. 10 Tho colonial minister\nhag recolved word from Dnkur, Heno\ngul, French West Africa, that a\nFrench column under idoutonunt Colo\nnel Moll had a desperate, engagement\nIn tho Ouadal region\" on Nov.! 0 with\ntho combined forces of tho sultans ol\nOuadal, Massallt und Doitdmourah\nand that tho tribesmen were ropuls-\ned with heavy loss.\nTip disputed! dooa not glvo an estl\nmuto'of tho French losses, but indi\ncates that thoy wore sovoro.\nColonel Moll and Lieutenant Joly arc\nreported to b0 among tho killed.\nTho minister hus cablod for dotulls.\nAN\nMASS MEETING\nUFLOCALWOMEN\nMarion Mothers Invited to\nAttend Session at Library\nForY. M.C. A.\nWOMEN WILL RAISE MONEY\nTo Save Association to the\nCity.\nDr. Thompson to Speak on\nSunday.\nKpwortli Church Kvenlng Service t'\nbo Ghcn Over to SpcnkeV Who --111\nPlead Y. 31. C. A. ,Caite Change\nIn .Sentiment Toward Campaign\nSocnw to Indicate Kinross It Is\n\"9.-0,000 or Bust.\"\nThat tho women of Marlon nro vi\ntally Interested In the Y. M. C. A.\ncampaign to ralso $50,000 and pre\nvent tho closing of tho association\nbecame ovldent today when follow\ning tho meeting t the building ltiBt\nnight at which the majority of tho\nclubs In the city wero represented, a\ncall was issued for a mass meeting\nto bo held Monday morning at nine\no'clock nt tho library building.\nThis meeting will be Important und\nevery woman In Marlon Is urged to\nattend, Dcflnlto plans of action will\nbo discussed and the most fouslble\nono determined upon. Tho women oi\nMurlon want to help in raising this\nmoney, und thoy realize that they are\nablo to do u great deal In -the way ol\nsecuring the tunas necessary\nDuring, tho past twenij'-iour hours\nthere has been u marked change In\nsentiment In regurd to the project.\nMen who Havo been opposed to iho\nrulslnglpof such a lurije sum for tho\ni'. M. C A. have learned more uboui\nIt; they.havo 'investigated und found\nout tho 'Wonderful good uu associa\ntion muy do in uny city und the\nposition this association will be In it\n(ho project Is successful. Many men\nwho refused to mako donations whun\ntho cumpulgn was inaugurated, have\nchanged their mind und given lurgo\nsums und touuy aro actively at\nwork soliciting others to give thui\ntho good work may go on.\nThere aro no two wiiyu about It.\nThis money must bo raised or the\ni.'. M. C. A- closed will bo closed.\nThis Is not said by tho trustees In\nspite but because It is an absolute und\ncertain fuct. Tho Y. M. C. A. is now\nIn debt $3,000 und It will tuko $i,UU\nto curry tho association fur tue next\ntwo ycurs. during which there wil.\nbo no public subscriptions usked tor.\nIf $50,000 is not rulsed none of the\npledges will bo collected. Tnuu llier.\nwill be no money on which to operate\nand tho association must of necessity\nclose Hs doors und with the closing\nMarlon will receivo the most set ere\nbackset In its history and unu thut\nwill tuko yours to overcome.\nYesterday Fred JO. Outhcry iniulu\nnn excellent uddrt.su to the workers.\nHo told them that they should go\nforth and loll the men of Marlon 'thai\nthis association needs help and as u\nmutter of public pride tho donations\nshould bo lurgc. Two years uro given\nto puy tho pledges und therefore\nthoy should be turgor than If the\ncash was being solicited.\nMr. UuUiery told his auditors that\nthey must inform the people of Ma\nrion that the Y, M. C. A. mum closo\nIf tho money Is not forthi'omlng.\nThere will not be sufficient funds to\ncarry on tho work unless tho mono)\nIs raised und tho trustees will have\nno cholco but to close.\nMr. Guthcry Bald thut ho believed\nMurlon big, broad and public-spirited\nenough to glvo this umouut. Ho said\nthat the Y, M. C. A. is tho best\ncharity In the world becuuso It does\nnot hand out food nnd clothing to\npaupers but accomplishes the, things\nthat glvo tho young man a chance\nto better himself In tho world. \"Give\nfood and clothing to paupers and\nthoy are paupers still; glvo a young\nman a better education und u hotter\nphyslclnl cond'tlon und you have made\na man.\"\nMr. Guthery said thut tho half\nhcurtedpess must be brought to an\nend. Tho workers from this Mine un\ntil next Wednesday night must put\nforth every effort and there must not\nbo u moment lost, No man should\nbo unsolicited,\nTomorrow speakers will pres\"iit the\nY. M. C. A. euuso to congregations\nIn the churches and President Thomp\nson of Ohio State Unlverblty will\nspeok for tho project In tho evening\nat Kpworth church. Dr. Thompson Is\na noted spenkor und Is well worth\ngoing far to lieur on uny topic thut\nho may chooso to speak on.\nMonday thoro will bo u renewal of\ntho campaign. Workers have agreed\nto stay In tho Held from Monday\nmorning to Wednesday night nnd\nenthusiastic effort of this sort is\ncertain to reach tho mark. Tho hand\nof tho clock on tho court house porti\nco should move around swiftly elui-\nIng the remainder of tho cumpulgn.\nTho Mirror today on this pugo prc\nsontB a replica of tho clock that Is\nstationed on tho court house. Watch\ntho hand move from day to day and\nho BUro that you nrH doing your\npart to help the hand move up to\ntho boys of the coming generation.\nY. M. C. A. Fund\nAre You Helping\nAnnounced Today by The\nCensus Bureau at Wash\nington the\nTOTAL BEING 91,972,266\nThat Being the Total Num\nber of People Scheduled\nBy the Agents of the\nGovernment\nFor Continental America\nBut Inclusive of the Philip\npine Islands The\nFigures Arc 1(11,10(1,(100 Iiic-rvuhu\nWry Lit ill In Aluskii Hut' Itofnnrk\nulilo in Must of the. Western Slates.\nBy tinned Press Wire.\nWashington, Dee. 10. Tho consus\noffleo today announced the present\npopulation of the continental United\nStntes ns yi.'J7i:.2fiG. Increase 15.077.-\n4J30GAT0\nHeading top to bottom General II.\nM. linker, cousin or Mrs, Uddy;\nClifford P. Smith reader mother\nchurch, Hoston. ltv. Irving C.\nTomllnson. member Mrs. Hddy's\nhousehold, and Adam H, Dlckoy,\nprivate' secretary \"nil member of\nboard of director. Upon thesa men\nw II full niuih of tho voik of di\nrecting tho nffahs of tho CJhrlstaln\nScience church hereafter.\nUNCLE SI'S\nPOPULATION\nWill m?4ms WM\nwin Arfv W\nb;'1 ZK- fKSJ\nIs Growing Fast.\nThis Hand Move?\nCSl, or 21 per rent. The population\nof tho United Stntes, Including speci\nfied dependencies, is 93,402,1 1, In\neroaso 10,145,521, or 20.9 per cent.\nThe population of the state or\nWashington Is 1,I41.!I90, Increase\n023,887, or 120.1 per vent. This gives\nWashington three more congressmen.\nTho population of the stnto of Wis\nconsin Is 2,333, SCO. Inercnse 261,818,\nor 12.7 per cent. This increase Is suf\nflclent for one more congressman.\nThe population of the state of\nGeorgia la 2,009.121, Increase 392,790,\nor 17 7 per cent. The Increase Is\nsufficient for one more congressman.\nIt was announced that tho total for\nNew York state had been corrected\nmaking It 9.113,011, increase 1,614,\n720, or 21.4 per cent.\nThe Increase Is sufficient for nine\nnew congressmen!.\nThe total for Florldu wns changed\nto rend 752,019, Increase 234.077, or\n4 2.0 per cent. Florida gets ono new\ncongressman.\nThe total for Alaska Is given as\nG4,350, Increase 764, nr 1.2 per cent.\nThe \"military and naval popula\ntion\" of the! United States was an\nnounced nt 55,608.\nThe totnl for Hawaii Is 191.909, In\ncrease 37,908, or 2l;jMor cent.\nThe ranking ordorlpf the states tin\ndor the new census follt5lvs:\"'rt!',\nNew York, Pennsylvania, Illinois.\nOhio. Texas, Massachusetts, Missouri.\nMichigan, Indiana. Georgia, New Jer\nsoy. California, Vjsconsln, Kontuelo,\nIowa, North Carolina. Tennessee. Al.i\nbanut, Minnesota, Virginia, Mississip\npi, Kansas, Oklahoma, Louisiana, Ar\nkansas. North Carolina, Maryland.\nWest Virginia. Nobrnska, Washington,\nPorto llico, Connecticut, Colorado\nFlorida, Maine, Oregon, South Dii;\nkota. North Dakota, Ithode Island,\nNow Hampshire. .Montana, Utah. Ver\nmont. District of Columbia, New Mex\nico, Idaho, ArUouu. Delaware, Hawaii\nWjomlng, Nevada, Alaska.\nPopulation of Montana, 370,053, in\ncrease 132,724, or 51.5 per cent. Tak\ning the population of the Philippine\nby the census of 1903, which win\n7,035,426, and adding the estimate\nfor the Islands of Guam nnd Samosa\nmid tho canal zone, a grand total for\ntho population of tho Unltod States\nund possessions Is given as 101,100,\n000.' \"Tho United States with speclllcd\ndependencies,\" Is understood by the\ncensus bureau in Include Alnska, Ha\nwaii, Porio Hleo and military und\nnaval persons abroad but not um\notner possessions or the United States\n\"Tho military nnd naval poputn\ntlon\" of the United States, which ten\nyeurs ago was 91,219 Includes the sol\ndiers and sailors on duty In tho Phlll'i\npines Porto Hleo, Hawaii, Alaska and\noilier dependencies but not those st i\ntloned In the United Stntes proper.\nTho fnct that many moro nion\nwere on duty In the Islands follow-\nIMPORTANT NOTICE\nTO ALL MERCHANTS\nA meeting at the Y.\nM. C. A. Monday even\ning to formulate plans\nfor securing contribu\ntions from out of town\nWholesale Houses.\nEven- Marion mer\nchant can secure con\ntributions from some of\nthe wholesale houses\nfrom whom he buys\ngoods.\nA mooting of all mer\nchants is called at tho\nY. M. C. A. at 7:30\no'clock, Monday even\ning, for this purpose by\ntho Merchants Associa\ntion. J. K, Philips, President.\nMorgan Burke, Secy.\nlug tho Spanish-American war than\nnow, accounts fur iho decrease since\n1900.\nMONACO PROCLAIMED\nA REPUBLIC TODAY\nBy United Press Wire\nLondon. Doc 10. The little prin\ncipality of Monaco, rhleily noted for\ntclng the site of Monte Carlo, hu\nbeen proclaimed u republic by Its\nmunlilpnl council, according to nn\nunconfirmed report in today's Pull\nMall Gazette. Prlnco Albert Is the\nruler of Monaco, which embraces but\neight square miles and Is surrounded\nby the From h department \"f Alpes\nMurltlinvs, except on Its .Mediterran\nean sea side.\nThe Homestead Steel\nWorks to Cast Armor\nPlate for Fortifying\nPanama Canal?\nUy United 1'rcsn Wire.\nPittsburg. Pa.. Dee. 10 An Ingot of\nKrupp steel weighing 135 tons Is III\nthe HonuntHad steel works today\nread to piessed Into an eighteen\nInch armor plate to no usoil on a\nland fort on the Panama canal. The\nsize of the Ingot breaks all world's\nrecords. A twin to It will be enst\nIn about two weeks.\nBY ELECTIONS\nAnd the Problem of the\nHouse of Lords Remains\nUnsolved.\nUy United Prom Wire\nI.0111I011, Dee. 10 With only 171\nout or 670 constituencies still to vote\nin tho general parliamentary election,\nthe futility of the struggle Is Indi\ncated by the fact that nt presont the\nConservatives and the Llbprnl-Liibor-Ite\nalliance have exactly the muni\nnumber of seats us they had from\nthe same constituencies In the Iusi\nelection.\nThe constltuonclVs yet to vote ni\nnot expected to effect uny mnterlul\nchange In the standing or the parties\nfrom the lust purllumcnt.\nTour I'lrr.\nClweliind, O., Dec. 10. Four lire\ncurly today caused a property Inhs of\nabout $110,000, drove men and women\nto the streets In their night clothes,\nwith several mil row escape's from\ndeath und suffering from the cold,\nTho plant or the Onbrlol Manufuc\nHiring compan.x. which makes the\nGabriel automobile horn, was totull)\ndestroyed. Th property loss Is esti\nmated at over $90.00(1 by H. Fostei.\nproprietor Onlv $20,000 Insurant-,\nwas carried. Th- II 10 spread to two\nadjoining houses, which were purth\ndestroyed. While these tires were be\nIng fought the department wns called\nto put out fires hi two oth-r localities\nSOTHERN GIVES FINE\nPERFORMANCE IN \"MACBETH\"\nNew York. Dee 10 K H. Sothem\nhas been a good nitor for many years,\nand he has pla.ed some Slutkespearu\nroles with fair suteess, but his moht\nanient admirer never expected him to\nglvo Htieh a Dulshed performance ns\nhe Is now playing In \"Macbeth\nTho Sothein-Murlowe revival of\nShukcspeare plays Is by all means the\nmost elaborate vcWvttl seen In this\ncity In many years. A'morlca ha\nnever seen n liner production of \"Mac\nbeth\" than that glvou by Mr. Sothern\nand Miss Marlowe.\nTho publln expects Miss Murlowo to'j\ntill acceptably uny rolo sho tries, and\nshe did not fall it as I-udy Macbeth.\nHut It Is Mr .Sothoni that lias won tho\nprnlho of the public and the orltlcs by\nhis performance. t\nMany changes havo biitn ntndo tu\ntho production, and nll'tojlho better\nment of the performance.\nTHIN DIlAIMSUIl'H\nLoudon, Doe 10. Since, the arrival\nof shadow dances tushlnn j)as dcolurcd\nthat thin draperies uro proper for ev\nening wear.\nA dress trimmed In liu-n1 nr covered\nwith .tho thinnest of fabrics Is proper,\naccording to Loudon dressmakers.\nW H 0\nAUTHORIZED\nwTjAjHXl K&, fiGfiSnHtH\nPOLICE HOPE\nTO GET BOSS\nOf the Big Kidnaping Or\nganization Which Has\nWidespread Operations\nTHE LEADER A BUSINESS MAN\nWho Does Not Live in New\nYork City And When Ar\nrested There Will Probably Follow\nA Startling Series of Dis\nclosures as Four\nChildren I line llccn Kidnaped With\nin the I.iil Sl'ty Diijh Somu of\nThese .Scoiiiulicls Already Identi\nfied. Ev United Press Wire\nNew York. Dec. 10. Within the\nnext few days the New York police\nhope to capture \"the boss\" In tho\n?nng of ttiilliin kidnapers, whose op\nerations are believed to have been the\nmost widespread and heartless III tho\nmunis of ibis form of crime.\nThrough Information obtained from\nMichael ltb.zo, the Italian boy kid\nuipeil along with Giuseppe I.ongo,\nfrom near his Brooklyn home on No\nember 19, Deputy Flynn believes he\ns at lust on the truck of the lender\nof the gang, ten of whose members\nwere captured In a raid on their east\nsixty-Third street head(iiurters nnJ\nire now held in $10,000 bull each,\n\"The boss\" Is said to be a business\nman who has directed the operations\nof the gang. He Is not n resident of\nVow York City. When he Is nrrcst\nd, the police believe n most startling\nprlos or disclosures will be forthcom\ning The (Hiding of the Longo and\nUliizo boys leaves four children kid\nnaped within the Inst sixty days still\nunaccounted for. It Is practically cor\nlain that all six children were stolen\nby the gang now being rounded up\nmil It Is believed the four mUsltlrf\n'hlldren will soon be abandoned on\nhe streets, as was the Hlzzo boy last\nnight.\nYoung Ul.zo today attempted to\nido IiIh Identification of certain mem.\nhers of the gang to that of Giuseppe\nKongo, who poslthely recognized\n\"Mffrla fluppa as the woman in wlioso\nhouse he was kept a prisoner, nnd\nC.'nndrnuo, alias Vlto Calorlno, as tho\nman who posed as the woman's hus\nband. HIhzo's story of the kidnaping\nerlneldes perfectly with that of Lou\ngo. The two boys are being detained In\nthe rooms or the children's society In\nUiookly'n, as the police are taking no\n1 nances on allowing tho lads to all\nnto the hands or rrlends of tho kid\nnapers or of being cowed by throats.\nUvea when members of their families\njail on them, 11 policeman who undor--minis\nin Han Is present.\nThis shows what a desperate crowd\nthe police believe they havo to deil\nwith I'lii'' uy there Is little doubt\nthat the hrys would either he mur\nloroil fr liven again, wero they al\n',owi d 1 1 go fri e\nOPIUM TAKEN\nAS CONTRABAND\nIn Sweeping Investiga\ntions And $16,000 Worth\nOf it Found Thirty-six\nChinamen in Jail.\nBy Culled Pre Wire.\nPittsburg Pa Dec. 10 As the cul\nmination of sweeping Investigations\nmade by federal authorities In Hoches\nter New York, and Philadelphia, $16,\n000 worth of opium Is In the hands of\nthe government here today and thirty\nsix Chinamen are In Jail held for hear\nIngs without h.tll-\nA Hlnuiltaneous raid In Philadel\nphia also resulted In lurge seizures\nof the contraband drug. According to\nDistrict Attorney Jordan nnd Cus\ntoms gent Austin Reynolds, who\nplanned the raids, tho \"dope\" Is bo-in-\nuniHc-simi into the country at tho\nport of Philadelphia where It Is ship\nped to Hochester and then to Pitts\nburg, where It Is alleged tho opium\nhabit among Chinese Is as cxtonslvo\nas anywhere in tho country, Th0 de\ntour lo Hochester Is to mislead tho\nauthorities, said the district attor\nney today.\nWORKING TO RESTORE\nMANUEL TO THROVE\nHy Unliert rrfc\" \"Wire.\nHomo. Dee, 10 Startling Portu\nguese divclopnient. having for their\nobject tne restoration of King Mun\nnni in Mi throne, uro declared to bo\nImminent In messagos received by\nManuol's f.lends nt the Italian court..\nCredence Is lven to tho report by\nthe statement that Dom Miguel.\nPnrtugueso pretender, has culled a\ni.nrnrniw.i of his followers, presum\nably to forestal: uny movo on Man\nuel's part.\nThroe Oil Tanks.\nFindluy, O.. Dec. 10. Flro destroy\ned three largo oil tanks belonging to\ntho Ohio Oil company early this\nmorning. Tho estimated low will be\nunwards of $25,000. Crossing of\nI trolley wires caused It.\nV4\nw\n1\n1","height":"27264","width":"21700"}}
